The paper proposes a novel approach for motion artifact correction in cardiovascular magnetic resonance (CMR) using deep learning, specifically using a deep residual network (ResNet) and adversarial training. This involves image processing and computer vision techniques, which are typically covered in the computer science sub-category of computer vision (cs.CV). The use of deep learning and adversarial training also suggests that the paper may fall under the sub-categories of machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), and neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE). Additionally, the paper involves the evaluation of edge detection results, which falls under the sub-category of multimedia (cs.MM).
